The thing is... with soooo many MMORPGs coming out in 2003 and 2004, common sense says that 80% of them will be dead within 6 months after release. <br>
<br>
IMHO the ones that will prosper and survive are the ones that provide an already rich background history (e.g. EQ's world of Norrath).  An MMORPG that wants long term success needs to be built on a foundation of an ever-expandable and ever-growing, never-stale world.  It needs to be a world that is rich with mythology, rich in legends, rich in geography (places to explore), a place where the players are always finding and discovering new things even after they had been playing the game for 11 or 15 months. <br>
<br>
There is a pragmatic reason for this logic also.  A world that feels ever-expanding and so rich in lore and history is an MMORPG that can be done with many future expansions.  That's exactly how SOE came out with numerous expansions, which fuels the corporate success of Everquest.  <br>
<br>
Norrath in EQ has done a great job with that.  And I predict that the universe of SWG will be equally as successful.  <br>
<br>
